The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the allocation of penicillin from mould fungi was not the first discovery of Fleming.
A few years earlier, when he was cold, he planted mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (a glass cap that was used to experiment with bacteria) and in a few days found that the bacteria there had been destroyed.
Almost as accidentally it was discovered and penicillin.
Fleming's name was inscribed on the list of 100 most prominent personalities in human history.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin medicine began to cope with most of the most ancient diseases, previously considered incurable,-tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming came to the French capital in 1945, the Parisian newspapers wrote: "For the defeat of Fascism and the liberation of France, he did more than dozens of divisions."
According to experts, the discovery of Fleming's first antibiotic in the world saved the lives of more than 200 million inhabitants of the Earth.
Alexander Fleming died in his home in London in 1955, from a heart attack.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in the famous London Cathedral of St. Paul.
Where, by the way, my wife and my attention to it drew a talkative speaking tour guide.
A few years later, the statue of Alexander Fleming in full growth we had a chance to observe in the most unexpected for this place in the capital of Spain.
There, near the main arena for the bullfighting of the Plaza de Toros de las Ventas, the famous Spanish matadors erected a monument to a man whose efforts were saved, in their opinion, by the lives of hundreds of outstanding masters of Corrida.
