The main Macedonian opposition activist refused to vote in a referendum
In Macedonia on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on the issue of an intergovernmental treaty with Greece on the renaming of the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting an agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party "Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization-the Democratic Party for the Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPME), Christian Mitkovsky, said that there would be no vote in the referendum.
According to the press secretary of the party Nahum Stoilkovsky, Mitkovsky decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the Treaty, which considers "detrimental".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum solves the issue of renaming the country and no more, whereas the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago the president of Macedonia Gheorghe Ivanov refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created," Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic-the Republic of northern Macedonia-was signed by the foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shores of the Prespa Lake, which passes the border Between the two countries.
This treaty should resolve the multi-year dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje way to NATO and the EU, reminiscent of TASS.
